WEBVTT

00:00.406 --> 00:02.840
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:04.640 --> 00:06.078
<i>They'll know everything very soon.</i>

00:06.109 --> 00:07.742
You're leaving? He'll
be here any second.

00:07.758 --> 00:08.891
Tell him I've gone to West Point.

00:08.925 --> 00:10.585
I have to hurry.

00:11.156 --> 00:13.929
- We have to come with you.
- I can barely make it as it is.

00:13.954 --> 00:15.598
If I take you both, he'll catch us.

00:15.820 --> 00:17.154
He needs to think you're innocent.

00:17.179 --> 00:18.414
You don't know anything, understand?

00:18.439 --> 00:20.436
He won't believe me.
He'll have me arrested.

00:20.470 --> 00:21.771
Make him believe you.

00:21.805 --> 00:23.673
This is the only way I
know to keep you safe.

00:23.707 --> 00:26.777
<i>♪</i>

00:27.811 --> 00:29.412
I love you.

00:29.446 --> 00:32.445
<i>♪</i>

00:35.418 --> 00:39.188
General Washington.
Your Excellency. Welcome.

00:39.222 --> 00:42.222
<i>♪</i>

00:44.000 --> 00:50.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:55.238 --> 00:57.651
Will he be much longer?

00:58.441 --> 01:00.743
Any moment, I'm... I'm sure.

01:02.850 --> 01:04.123
[floorboards creaking]

01:04.149 --> 01:05.865
Your Excellency.

01:06.049 --> 01:09.049
<i>♪</i>

01:18.061 --> 01:20.396
Ready. Up.

01:20.430 --> 01:22.832
<i>♪</i>

01:22.866 --> 01:25.501
- What is your business?
- Don't shoot.

01:25.810 --> 01:28.168
- Did you know?
- Your Excellency, I...

01:28.193 --> 01:30.840
- Did you know?
- No, no, he wouldn't.

01:30.874 --> 01:32.842
[baby crying]

01:32.876 --> 01:35.876
<i>♪</i>

01:40.851 --> 01:43.435
Who are you?

01:44.240 --> 01:46.255
My name's Benedict Arnold.

01:46.289 --> 01:48.157
I've come to help you win the war.

01:48.191 --> 01:51.227
<i>[music intensifying]</i>

02:01.972 --> 02:03.572
How are they?

02:03.607 --> 02:06.075
Olivia's conked out,
and I just busted Mark

02:06.109 --> 02:08.176
playing that crazy-violent
video game again.

02:08.211 --> 02:10.780
Thank you so much for having me.

02:10.814 --> 02:13.744
A home-cooked meal is a rare and
exotic thing in my life these days.

02:13.769 --> 02:15.694
Believe me, it was my pleasure.

02:15.719 --> 02:17.453
You're a professor?

02:17.487 --> 02:20.423
The history and anthropology
of American political movements.

02:20.457 --> 02:22.625
That alone makes you the
most interesting colleague

02:22.659 --> 02:24.460
of Denise's I've ever met. [chuckles]

02:24.494 --> 02:26.762
Ignore her. She's teasing me.

02:26.797 --> 02:29.131
It also makes you the only
colleague I've ever met.

02:29.166 --> 02:31.233
17 years, nada.

02:31.268 --> 02:33.235
Michelle. [laughs]

02:33.270 --> 02:35.371
Hey, I don't ask questions.

02:35.405 --> 02:38.607
And knowing what she
does, I don't want to ask.

02:38.642 --> 02:41.908
But out of the blue, it's,
"Make the mustard chicken.

02:41.933 --> 02:43.646
"Lucy Preston's coming over."

02:43.680 --> 02:46.315
Must have some kind of superpower.

02:46.349 --> 02:47.883
What is it?

02:47.918 --> 02:49.585
To be honest, it, uh,

02:49.619 --> 02:51.821
came as a surprise to me too.

02:53.161 --> 02:55.129
[water running]

03:01.025 --> 03:02.965
Your family is lovely.

03:02.999 --> 03:06.383
Thanks. I wanted you to meet them.

03:06.408 --> 03:09.271
But your wife does have a point.

03:09.306 --> 03:10.739
Why did you invite me over?

03:10.774 --> 03:15.411
I've been up most
nights lately worrying.

03:15.445 --> 03:17.146
I know that Rufus talked to you about...

03:17.180 --> 03:18.981
Rittenhouse? Yeah, that's part of it.

03:19.015 --> 03:20.950
And I'm looking into it, believe me.

03:20.984 --> 03:25.187
But what's really been keeping
me awake is your mother.

03:25.222 --> 03:26.489
My mother?

03:26.523 --> 03:30.459
As hard as it must be for
you to remember your sister,

03:30.494 --> 03:32.461
what's worse for me...

03:32.496 --> 03:34.463
is that your mother doesn't.

03:34.498 --> 03:39.000
She had a daughter she
doesn't even know existed.

03:39.469 --> 03:41.537
Before the time machine,

03:41.571 --> 03:44.773
my worst fear was losing them.

03:45.141 --> 03:47.877
Now it's that I could lose them

03:47.911 --> 03:50.179
and not know they were ever here.

03:50.213 --> 03:51.780
I get it, Lucy.

03:51.815 --> 03:55.065
The pressure you must
feel keeping history intact

03:55.090 --> 03:59.135
so more people aren't just... erased.

04:00.891 --> 04:03.200
I want you to do me a favor.

04:05.395 --> 04:07.496
Keep this in the Lifeboat for me.

04:07.531 --> 04:11.166
<i>[pensive music]</i>

04:11.201 --> 04:12.848
What is it?

04:13.858 --> 04:15.551
It's them.

04:17.551 --> 04:22.067
Pictures, photographs, kindergarten art.

04:22.748 --> 04:25.920
It's our life in a disk.

04:26.850 --> 04:31.264
If you come back someday
and they are gone...

04:33.356 --> 04:35.691
promise you'll show it to me

04:35.725 --> 04:38.680
and tell me everything about tonight.

04:41.197 --> 04:45.071
I need to know they existed.

04:47.437 --> 04:49.305
[whispers] Yeah.

04:57.354 --> 05:00.249
It's not... it's not sexist
if I use a woman to beat you.

05:00.290 --> 05:02.708
[chuckles] All right, we gotta go.

05:02.886 --> 05:04.453
[knock at door]

05:04.487 --> 05:06.088
- Pause button.
- Oh, I can pay for it.

05:06.122 --> 05:07.990
I can afford pizza, Rufus.

05:08.926 --> 05:11.190
- Hey.
- Oh, hello, Jiya.

05:11.215 --> 05:13.562
Sorry to intrude.

05:13.597 --> 05:15.731
Glad you two are a thing, by the way.

05:15.765 --> 05:17.766
- What are you doing here?
- I need to speak to him.

05:17.801 --> 05:19.068
Privately, if you don't mind.

05:19.102 --> 05:21.185
Connor, this is her apartment.

05:21.210 --> 05:23.572
Oh, chivalry. Nevertheless.

05:23.607 --> 05:25.307
I won't take long.

05:25.342 --> 05:27.226
It's all right.

05:32.682 --> 05:35.540
- Are you drunk?
- No.

05:36.019 --> 05:39.063
Yes. Slightly.

05:40.123 --> 05:44.540
I ever tell you my mother
used to, uh... clean houses?

05:44.928 --> 05:47.896
I'd watch her wrestle that
octopus of a vacuum cleaner

05:47.931 --> 05:49.732
of hers and I just wanted to help her.

05:49.766 --> 05:52.001
I just... I thought I could
invent a better one than that.

05:52.035 --> 05:54.503
- And so I did.
- Why are you telling me this?

05:54.537 --> 05:57.633
So then came the solar panels...

05:58.842 --> 06:00.509
the cars...

06:00.543 --> 06:01.656
[chuckles]

06:03.513 --> 06:07.449
and the stocks,
investors, the bottom line.

06:07.484 --> 06:11.163
But I didn't want any of that, really.

06:12.468 --> 06:14.765
I just want to turn a wrench,

06:15.158 --> 06:17.593
make my mother's life a little easier.

06:18.848 --> 06:20.529
Like you.

06:24.701 --> 06:26.795
I'm not a bad guy.

06:29.873 --> 06:33.660
I didn't mean to get
you into this so deeply.

06:34.411 --> 06:37.012
If I'd known it would end this way...

06:37.047 --> 06:39.129
End what way?

06:43.353 --> 06:46.789
Rittenhouse knows you've been
tampering with these recorders.

06:46.823 --> 06:49.158
[scoffs] No, I haven't. I...

06:49.192 --> 06:50.984
They know.

06:51.995 --> 06:55.464
So... last chance.

06:55.498 --> 06:59.529
Whatever the next mission
is, record it properly.

07:00.270 --> 07:01.904
If you don't, I can't protect you

07:01.938 --> 07:04.959
or your family anymore.

07:10.957 --> 07:13.091
I really am very sorry.

07:15.472 --> 07:17.100
Good night.

07:18.955 --> 07:21.924
<i>[pensive music]</i>

07:21.958 --> 07:24.958
<i>♪</i>

07:26.730 --> 07:28.664
What was that about?

07:28.698 --> 07:31.400
[phones chiming]

07:36.372 --> 07:37.873
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

07:37.907 --> 07:40.175
Flynn went to September 25, 1780.

07:40.210 --> 07:42.578
Let me guess, just north of Manhattan.

07:42.612 --> 07:45.047
<i>- How'd you know?</i>
- Oh, this is bad.

07:45.081 --> 07:46.715
This is really, really bad.

07:46.750 --> 07:48.117
What would Flynn want in New York City

07:48.142 --> 07:49.490
in the middle of the Revolutionary War?

07:49.515 --> 07:51.253
<i>It's not New York City; it's West Point.</i>

07:51.287 --> 07:52.921
- The Military Academy?
- In 1780,

07:52.956 --> 07:54.723
West Point was just a
fort, but Washington thought

07:54.758 --> 07:56.859
whoever controlled it would win the war.

07:56.893 --> 07:59.061
So what happened on September 25th?

07:59.103 --> 08:01.044
<i>Well, Washington was over at
Benedict Arnold's house for breakfast</i>

08:01.069 --> 08:04.800
when he learned that Arnold was plotting
to give West Point to the British.

08:04.834 --> 08:06.647
And Arnold fled before
Washington got there.

08:06.672 --> 08:07.970
<i>Benedict Arnold, huh?</i>

08:08.004 --> 08:09.805
The guy whose name basically
means "total jerk-off."

08:09.839 --> 08:12.105
He was Washington's
most brilliant general

08:12.130 --> 08:13.308
and trusted friend.

08:13.343 --> 08:15.778
Yeah, but Arnold's big
plan failed, obviously.

08:15.812 --> 08:17.446
Maybe Flynn wants to help him succeed,

08:17.480 --> 08:18.814
maybe help the British win the war?

08:18.848 --> 08:19.958
[chuckles] Bully for him.

08:19.983 --> 08:21.917
<i>Guys, do you realize
how bad this could be?</i>

08:21.951 --> 08:24.052
George Washington is at West Point

08:24.087 --> 08:25.754
the morning that Benedict Arnold fled.

08:25.789 --> 08:27.489
You think Flynn is trying
to kill George Washington?

08:27.524 --> 08:29.591
I don't know, but I'm on my way.

08:29.626 --> 08:32.327
[whirring]

08:32.361 --> 08:35.063
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

08:35.097 --> 08:37.299
[warbling tone]

08:42.366 --> 08:43.907
[chuckles]

08:45.642 --> 08:48.642
<i>♪</i>

08:55.785 --> 08:59.611
This is it. This is
Benedict Arnold's house.

08:59.636 --> 09:02.837
- Nice digs.
- Arnold had expensive tastes.

09:02.862 --> 09:04.827
He one time spent £1,000,

09:04.861 --> 09:06.428
which would be like $80,000 today,

09:06.462 --> 09:07.519
on one bottle of wine.

09:07.544 --> 09:10.987
- What? Who does that?
- A Grade A douche nozzle.

09:12.193 --> 09:13.992
Come on.

09:14.485 --> 09:16.055
Okay.

09:17.796 --> 09:20.064
So when does Washington show up?

09:20.089 --> 09:21.923
I don't know exactly.

09:22.307 --> 09:23.741
It doesn't look like anyone's here.

09:23.766 --> 09:24.980
Did we miss Flynn?

09:25.014 --> 09:26.682
Maybe he already helped Arnold escape.

09:26.716 --> 09:28.453
Stop!

09:28.478 --> 09:29.818
Don't move!

09:29.853 --> 09:31.687
- We're patriots.
- Quiet!

09:31.721 --> 09:34.223
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

09:34.257 --> 09:36.586
More traitors?

09:39.492 --> 09:41.493
Who are you?

09:42.055 --> 09:44.700
And what the hell are you doing here?

09:45.202 --> 09:47.502
Your Excellency.

09:47.817 --> 09:49.251
General Washington.

09:49.276 --> 09:52.276
<i>♪</i>

09:54.444 --> 09:57.412
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

09:57.454 --> 10:01.483
<font color="#007700">Synced and corrected by Aaronnmb</font>
www.addic7ed.com

10:01.733 --> 10:03.384
Your Excellency?

10:03.425 --> 10:04.710
That's what they called him.

10:04.735 --> 10:06.717
He won't be president
for ten more years.

10:06.855 --> 10:09.590
I know I should be getting
used to all of this by now,

10:09.625 --> 10:11.459
but this one...

10:11.493 --> 10:14.128
What? That it's George Washington
or that he might want to kill us?

10:14.162 --> 10:16.998
Both. Maybe.

10:17.032 --> 10:18.317
I think both.

10:18.349 --> 10:19.582
[door creaks open]

10:22.285 --> 10:25.287
Easy, easy. I got a
man in the next room.

10:25.312 --> 10:27.642
If shots go off in here,
he shoots Washington.

10:27.676 --> 10:28.866
You're bluffing.

10:28.891 --> 10:30.778
You're talking to the
man who shot Lincoln.

10:30.812 --> 10:33.139
You really want to take that risk?

10:33.515 --> 10:36.255
Just put the gun away.

10:37.853 --> 10:40.177
I need your help.

10:41.026 --> 10:42.700
Our help?

10:43.492 --> 10:46.401
The gun? Please?

10:47.119 --> 10:49.353
You really want to risk
killing George Washington?

10:49.378 --> 10:51.111
- What the hell is this?
- When he comes in,

10:51.136 --> 10:53.729
just nod and follow my lead.

10:54.136 --> 10:57.983
Or else I'll have Washington
hang you for treason.

10:58.240 --> 10:59.674
Come on!

10:59.708 --> 11:00.987
Wyatt.

11:01.031 --> 11:02.112
[door creaking]

11:03.499 --> 11:04.961
Well...

11:07.849 --> 11:10.570
Are you who this man says you are?

11:12.500 --> 11:15.356
Well, that's a
complicated question, sir.

11:15.390 --> 11:18.703
Yes. Yes, we are.

11:18.728 --> 11:22.621
Mr. Roe here says you're the best
spies he's got in the Culper Ring.

11:22.646 --> 11:24.465
Yes, that's him.

11:24.499 --> 11:28.736
Mr. Austin Roe, the
renowned Prussian spy.

11:28.761 --> 11:30.769
Well, thank God for him.

11:31.406 --> 11:34.675
He's the one who warned
me about Arnold's betrayal,

11:34.710 --> 11:37.888
though the bastard still
slipped through our fingers.

11:37.913 --> 11:40.815
And you, you're a free man?

11:40.849 --> 11:44.051
And a hell of a spy.
I'm very unassuming.

11:44.086 --> 11:46.587
I'd like to tell them about the mission.

11:46.621 --> 11:47.650
The mission?

11:47.675 --> 11:49.861
The four of you are to
head into redcoat territory

11:49.886 --> 11:51.892
and capture Benedict Arnold.

11:51.927 --> 11:55.500
Say you were inspired
by Arnold's example.

11:55.897 --> 11:58.199
You'll find him and bring him back.

11:58.233 --> 12:00.063
To justice.

12:01.436 --> 12:02.770
Is there a problem?

12:02.804 --> 12:05.206
No, no, no. There's no problem.

12:05.240 --> 12:06.662
Right?

12:07.167 --> 12:09.358
No. No, sir.

12:10.217 --> 12:11.412
We'd be glad to help.

12:11.446 --> 12:14.795
Bring him to me. Alive.

12:15.317 --> 12:18.252
I want to look him in
the eye one last time...

12:18.286 --> 12:20.287
before I hang him.

12:22.324 --> 12:25.426
Why would Washington
believe you were a spy.

12:25.460 --> 12:28.062
Because even though George
Washington trusted Roe,

12:28.096 --> 12:29.964
they never actually met face-to-face.

12:29.998 --> 12:33.267
So where is the real Austin Roe?

12:33.301 --> 12:35.603
- Dead in a ditch.
- You're a bastard.

12:35.637 --> 12:38.305
- What is all this, Flynn?
- I need Lucy.

12:39.041 --> 12:40.975
She'll know how to find Arnold.

12:41.009 --> 12:42.643
She knows everything about him.

12:42.677 --> 12:44.267
Why? So you can help him?

12:44.328 --> 12:46.362
Oh, I'm not gonna help Arnold.

12:46.387 --> 12:48.415
But I'm not taking him
back to Washington either.

12:48.450 --> 12:49.817
I'm gonna interrogate him,

12:49.851 --> 12:51.352
probably beat the hell out of him.

12:51.386 --> 12:53.421
Interrogate him? About what?

12:53.455 --> 12:57.458
That key from Bonnie and Clyde
opened an interesting door.

12:57.492 --> 12:59.385
Or clock.

12:59.895 --> 13:03.030
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:03.065 --> 13:06.065
<i>♪</i>

13:12.140 --> 13:15.076
- It's invisible ink.
- Read it.

13:17.546 --> 13:18.946
It's a letter Benedict Arnold wrote.

13:18.980 --> 13:22.110
It says something about
a Rittenhouse meeting.

13:22.135 --> 13:24.278
Are you telling me that Benedict Arnold

13:24.303 --> 13:25.475
was a member of Rittenhouse?

13:25.500 --> 13:28.956
Wasn't just a member.
He was a founding member.

13:28.990 --> 13:31.892
This is the year they
began. This is our chance.

13:31.927 --> 13:34.048
We're gonna kill
Rittenhouse in the crib.

13:34.073 --> 13:35.896
We're gonna stop them
before they ever get started.

13:35.931 --> 13:37.720
- We can't talk about this.
- You're gonna hunt these people down,

13:37.745 --> 13:39.915
- and you want us to help you?
- We can't talk about this.

13:39.940 --> 13:42.403
Why? Because of your
secret little recorder?

13:42.437 --> 13:44.505
What? You don't think I know?

13:44.539 --> 13:49.410
Okay, I'll make this easy.
You help me here, now,

13:49.444 --> 13:52.179
and I'll hand over the keys
to the Mothership, all yours.

13:52.214 --> 13:53.981
After all, once Rittenhouse is gone,

13:54.015 --> 13:55.983
why would I keep taking
these godforsaken trips?

13:56.017 --> 13:57.985
You're talking about killing
people, changing history.

13:58.019 --> 14:00.254
One last time and then it's over.

14:00.288 --> 14:02.423
That, or you keep chasing me,

14:02.457 --> 14:04.483
and I change history
a hundred more times.

14:04.508 --> 14:07.404
Or we can end this, Lucy, now,

14:07.429 --> 14:09.063
once and for all.

14:16.771 --> 14:18.362
Here.

14:18.387 --> 14:21.659
Your journal. Show of faith.

14:21.776 --> 14:23.911
See for yourself how bad
Rittenhouse really is.

14:23.945 --> 14:26.113
See in your own words.

14:29.317 --> 14:33.454
You're so full of crap,
it's coming out of your ears.

14:33.488 --> 14:36.524
We're not gonna help you, not
after everything we've been through.

14:36.558 --> 14:38.624
I figured you'd say that.

14:39.574 --> 14:41.842
So I'm sweetening the pot.

14:41.867 --> 14:44.132
You help me,

14:44.297 --> 14:48.569
and I'll tell you what happened
on Portero Road, mile marker 47.

14:49.437 --> 14:52.616
That's right, I'll give you
the name of your wife's killer.

14:57.812 --> 15:00.590
You have no idea who
could have done that.

15:00.615 --> 15:03.717
I'm not some local cop, Wyatt.

15:03.752 --> 15:06.220
I've still got some
friends in the right places.

15:06.254 --> 15:09.056
There was blood on the scene,
right, that wasn't Jessica's?

15:09.090 --> 15:12.179
That they never matched?
Well, I know whose it was.

15:13.138 --> 15:17.429
So you help me get Benedict Arnold,

15:18.133 --> 15:20.312
no more Rittenhouse.

15:21.440 --> 15:23.936
No more chasing me through time.

15:25.373 --> 15:28.364
Your wife's killer found.

15:30.111 --> 15:32.012
Everybody wins.

15:42.666 --> 15:45.134
Well, there goes recording.

15:45.169 --> 15:47.170
There's no amount of tampering
that is gonna hide the fact

15:47.195 --> 15:50.034
that we are helping
Flynn destroy Rittenhouse.

15:50.393 --> 15:52.141
My life is literally over.

15:52.176 --> 15:53.609
Not if we wipe them from the map.

15:53.644 --> 15:54.977
You're seriously considering this?

15:55.012 --> 15:56.546
Helping out a terrorist?

15:56.580 --> 15:58.915
That makes us a bunch of
Benedict Arnolds, you know that?

15:58.940 --> 16:01.673
- You've had better jokes.
- Well, I'm nervous.

16:02.555 --> 16:04.523
You can't tell me you
actually trust Flynn.

16:04.548 --> 16:08.351
No, of course not, but if
there is even a 1% chance

16:08.376 --> 16:11.236
that he really knows
who Jessica's killer is?

16:12.362 --> 16:14.030
Where do you come out on this?

16:14.064 --> 16:16.777
If this is true, Rittenhouse has
their fingerprints all over...

16:16.802 --> 16:18.849
the Trail of Tears, Jonestown Massacre,

16:18.874 --> 16:20.903
the Waco Siege, but
it's all still history,

16:20.938 --> 16:23.466
which is what we're supposed
to protect, even the bad stuff.

16:23.867 --> 16:25.401
Aren't we?

16:25.733 --> 16:28.768
- Everyone ready?
- Ready for what?

16:28.793 --> 16:30.513
There's a British Garrison up the road.

16:30.547 --> 16:31.857
We go defect.

16:31.882 --> 16:34.693
And why would the British
believe that we're defectors?

16:35.919 --> 16:38.888
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

16:38.922 --> 16:40.711
<i>♪</i>

16:40.751 --> 16:41.798
[gunfire]

16:41.823 --> 16:43.179
Do they have to make it look so real?

16:43.204 --> 16:44.227
Help! We're deserters!

16:44.261 --> 16:46.062
- Get ready!
- We're deserters!

16:46.096 --> 16:47.163
Don't shoot! Don't shoot!

16:47.197 --> 16:48.633
Get down! Fire!

16:48.658 --> 16:51.204
[gunfire]

16:51.229 --> 16:54.229
<i>♪</i>

17:15.242 --> 17:17.644
Okay, Lucy, you're up.

17:17.828 --> 17:21.222
General Arnold. You asked to see me.

17:21.773 --> 17:23.375
General Clinton sent us.

17:23.433 --> 17:24.777
We are loyalists, sir.

17:24.801 --> 17:26.941
- Inspired by your example.
- Is that so?

17:26.965 --> 17:28.925
We have covert information for you,

17:28.950 --> 17:31.378
about Washington's troop movements.

17:33.957 --> 17:36.005
I received no word from General Clinton.

17:36.030 --> 17:38.332
Clinton was supposed to send it.

17:41.285 --> 17:43.286
[whispering] Confidentially,

17:43.312 --> 17:47.113
you and I both know General
Clinton can be a bit... erratic.

17:47.651 --> 17:50.119
Perhaps a touch of his mother's lunacy.

17:50.419 --> 17:52.787
And you've met this man before.

17:52.829 --> 17:54.463
You fought with him at Ridgefield.

17:54.498 --> 17:56.972
He served under Colonel Lamb.

17:59.503 --> 18:02.171
Yes, that's right. I did.

18:02.206 --> 18:04.674
It's so good to see you again, sir.

18:04.708 --> 18:07.677
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:07.711 --> 18:10.711
<i>♪</i>

18:12.349 --> 18:15.851
Yes, I think I remember after all.

18:15.886 --> 18:18.154
Of course. [chuckles lightly]

18:18.188 --> 18:19.817
This way.

18:19.842 --> 18:22.856
<i>♪</i>

18:23.860 --> 18:25.661
[door rattles open]

18:26.239 --> 18:29.465
Let me introduce Earl Cornwallis.

18:29.499 --> 18:31.200
These are loyalists to the cause.

18:31.235 --> 18:32.544
Madam.

18:32.569 --> 18:34.481
They've come bearing gifts.

18:34.630 --> 18:37.340
So what's Washington's
plan for his troops?

18:37.374 --> 18:39.041
Could we speak in private, sir?

18:39.076 --> 18:41.877
These are trustworthy men.
Say what you've come to say.

18:41.912 --> 18:44.213
We've defected because
of your example, General.

18:44.248 --> 18:45.909
We'd prefer to speak only with you.

18:45.934 --> 18:48.113
Well, Madam, I'm not sure you're
in any place to make that decision.

18:48.138 --> 18:49.448
Come on!

18:49.841 --> 18:51.299
- [muffled gunshots]
- [gasps]

18:51.973 --> 18:53.369
What the hell?

18:53.871 --> 18:54.995
Stay away!

18:55.913 --> 18:58.981
- What the hell is going on?
- Managing the situation.

19:00.890 --> 19:02.824
You just killed Cornwallis.

19:02.849 --> 19:04.589
In 20 years, he's supposed to negotiate

19:04.614 --> 19:05.987
the peace treaty between
Britain and Napoleon.

19:06.012 --> 19:07.637
So history will find someone else.

19:07.671 --> 19:09.917
You see one redcoat, you've
seen them all. Big deal.

19:09.942 --> 19:12.081
It's a very big deal.

19:12.609 --> 19:14.377
Rufus, the curtains.

19:14.411 --> 19:16.768
I gotta find a place to
hide the bodies, quick.

19:21.184 --> 19:23.212
You're Washington's men?

19:23.237 --> 19:26.493
No, no, no. Washington's
men never find you.

19:26.556 --> 19:29.275
Actually, you're meant
to get away scot-free,

19:29.300 --> 19:31.370
live a comfortable life in England.

19:31.395 --> 19:33.126
Then who are you?

19:34.098 --> 19:35.579
Honestly?

19:36.884 --> 19:39.919
We're, uh, time travelers
from the year 2016

19:39.944 --> 19:42.407
who came all the way
here just to meet you.

19:46.810 --> 19:50.140
[laughing]

19:50.873 --> 19:52.774
- You're mad.
- Yeah.

19:52.816 --> 19:53.999
It doesn't matter who we are.

19:54.024 --> 19:56.768
What matters is what we need to know...

19:56.793 --> 19:58.749
about Rittenhouse.

20:00.979 --> 20:03.468
I don't know what you're talking about.

20:09.132 --> 20:11.334
This is your handwriting, isn't it?

20:14.671 --> 20:18.708
"Today I met some gentlemen
with a great vision for America.

20:18.742 --> 20:20.476
"Rittenhouse.

20:20.510 --> 20:23.776
"They're recruiting worthy
men and have sought me out."

20:25.616 --> 20:27.529
I never wrote that.

20:27.851 --> 20:30.152
Maybe we could help you remember.

20:30.187 --> 20:32.988
Beat me to death, have
Washington hang me.

20:33.023 --> 20:34.873
I don't know what you're talking about.

20:34.898 --> 20:38.810
I understand, understand why
you would betray Washington,

20:38.862 --> 20:40.129
why you would go to Rittenhouse.

20:40.163 --> 20:42.164
You must know me well.

20:42.199 --> 20:45.568
<i>[pensive music]</i>

20:45.602 --> 20:47.553
Well, I...

20:47.654 --> 20:51.440
I know you sank your entire
fortune into the Patriot cause.

20:51.475 --> 20:55.032
I know that you were one of
Washington's best and brightest.

20:55.097 --> 20:57.131
At Saratoga,

20:57.447 --> 20:59.582
when they shot your horse
dead right from underneath you,

20:59.616 --> 21:01.016
you kept fighting.

21:01.051 --> 21:04.891
And when a musket ball
shattered your leg,

21:04.916 --> 21:06.264
what did you do? You kept fighting.

21:06.289 --> 21:07.806
What of it?

21:08.125 --> 21:10.346
But when it came time...

21:10.371 --> 21:11.927
[sighs]

21:11.962 --> 21:15.297
for your promotion to Major General,

21:15.332 --> 21:17.971
the promotion that you earned,

21:18.235 --> 21:21.670
Congress just passed
you over, didn't they?

21:21.705 --> 21:23.305
[chuckles]

21:23.340 --> 21:26.518
And what did Washington do for you?

21:29.182 --> 21:30.582
Nothing.

21:34.084 --> 21:35.671
And so, uh,

21:37.312 --> 21:41.557
you betrayed him, you betrayed
everything that you once believed in.

21:41.591 --> 21:43.187
But for what?

21:43.992 --> 21:45.027
Pride?

21:45.061 --> 21:47.375
He betrayed me.

21:48.218 --> 21:50.332
He was my brother,

21:50.367 --> 21:52.656
and he abandoned me.

21:53.608 --> 21:55.663
But Rittenhouse,

21:56.072 --> 21:58.707
he's gonna give me the
future that I deserve.

21:58.742 --> 22:03.218
And no one, not you,
not anyone, will stop us.

22:03.265 --> 22:05.815
Wait. Did you just say "he"?

22:05.849 --> 22:08.085
The man you're asking
about, David Rittenhouse.

22:08.110 --> 22:10.390
Rittenhouse isn't a
they, it's one person?

22:10.415 --> 22:13.601
He has more followers
every day, but yes.

22:15.392 --> 22:17.515
[whispering] Did you know about this?

22:17.968 --> 22:19.695
- That it was just one man?
- No.

22:19.720 --> 22:23.032
It wasn't anywhere. I-it
wasn't in the journal.

22:23.066 --> 22:26.585
What journal? What
are you talking about?

22:29.739 --> 22:31.919
Introduce us to him.

22:32.576 --> 22:35.678
A woman? A negro?

22:35.712 --> 22:37.746
You're insane.

22:37.781 --> 22:39.802
He'd see her in his bed
and him in the fields.

22:39.827 --> 22:42.263
You will introduce us to him.

22:42.686 --> 22:45.454
And why would I ever do that?

22:48.291 --> 22:51.527
Washington's holding your wife prisoner.

22:51.552 --> 22:54.585
If we haven't returned
with you in three days,

22:54.611 --> 22:57.891
he will execute her for your treason.

23:02.272 --> 23:05.875
So take us to Rittenhouse,
and save your wife.

23:05.909 --> 23:09.044
<i>[pensive music]</i>

23:09.079 --> 23:12.047
The things we all do for love.

23:12.082 --> 23:15.082
<i>♪</i>

23:19.901 --> 23:22.068
Okay, Arnold and Flynn
will be down any second.

23:22.093 --> 23:23.792
What do we think?

23:25.080 --> 23:26.683
I'm in.

23:27.761 --> 23:30.113
You were the one that said we
were a bunch of Benedict Arnolds.

23:30.138 --> 23:32.480
That was before Rittenhouse
was just one dude.

23:32.613 --> 23:34.455
If all we gotta do is stop one guy...

23:34.480 --> 23:36.216
What? So we just kill him?

23:36.371 --> 23:38.218
We just kill him in cold blood?

23:38.252 --> 23:40.238
Wyatt's killed before.

23:41.417 --> 23:42.989
So have I.

23:43.441 --> 23:47.127
If this one move cuts
the head off the snake,

23:47.410 --> 23:50.312
wipes Rittenhouse out,
frees me from them,

23:50.337 --> 23:52.938
frees my family, then my vote...

23:55.774 --> 23:57.542
my vote is yes.

23:57.576 --> 23:59.383
I vote yes too.

24:05.859 --> 24:08.701
If we do this, then
history's gonna change.

24:08.726 --> 24:10.922
And what if... what if more
people vanish like my sister?

24:10.956 --> 24:12.757
What if more people are saved?

24:12.791 --> 24:17.228
Hell, what if you come home to Amy?

24:21.967 --> 24:23.512
Lucy,

24:24.178 --> 24:27.776
this isn't saving the
Moon launch or the Alamo.

24:27.801 --> 24:31.943
This is killing one evil son of a bitch,

24:31.977 --> 24:35.635
to save maybe hundreds of lives.

24:35.660 --> 24:38.249
I'm sorry, I don't think
that "history" is an excuse

24:38.283 --> 24:40.895
to sit back and let people suffer.

24:42.654 --> 24:45.390
I know you well enough by now.

24:45.424 --> 24:49.223
What you really believe
in is helping people.

24:50.996 --> 24:54.727
But, hey, we're in this together, so...

24:55.567 --> 24:58.665
So are we all ready to do this?

24:59.972 --> 25:02.743
Lucy, are we ready?

25:02.768 --> 25:05.157
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:05.182 --> 25:06.454
Yeah.

25:06.512 --> 25:09.512
<i>♪</i>

25:20.976 --> 25:22.791
Whoa.

25:26.198 --> 25:28.466
Horses need water.

25:28.500 --> 25:30.001
And I could use a thunder mug.

25:30.035 --> 25:31.544
Sounds amazing. Me too.

25:31.569 --> 25:33.337
What do you drink in a thunder mug?

25:33.372 --> 25:35.280
You urinate into it.

25:35.305 --> 25:38.468
Right, of course. Totally knew that.

25:39.978 --> 25:42.978
<i>♪</i>

25:57.624 --> 26:00.523
Hey, buddy. Hey.

26:01.200 --> 26:03.201
Hey, buddy.

26:10.142 --> 26:12.477
You know about horses?

26:12.511 --> 26:15.221
I wanted to be a cowboy growing up.

26:16.148 --> 26:20.768
You ever heard of,
uh, Tex Willer comics?

26:20.793 --> 26:23.120
He had a horse named Dynamite.

26:23.155 --> 26:26.351
They protected the good
guys against the bad guys.

26:31.363 --> 26:34.632
I hate to be a told-you-so, but, um,

26:34.666 --> 26:37.969
the journal did say something
about you and me working together?

26:38.003 --> 26:40.482
- Don't push your luck.
- Fair enough.

26:43.075 --> 26:44.943
Say we do this.

26:45.711 --> 26:47.717
That we really...

26:48.080 --> 26:50.177
take out Rittenhouse.

26:52.518 --> 26:54.638
Then what will you do?

26:55.554 --> 26:57.822
Go home to my family.

26:57.856 --> 26:59.982
They'll be alive again.

27:01.293 --> 27:04.195
Let my little girl jump into my arms.

27:04.229 --> 27:06.230
Hug my wife.

27:08.767 --> 27:11.168
And then say good-bye
and walk away forever.

27:11.203 --> 27:12.697
What?

27:14.306 --> 27:16.384
You would just...

27:16.808 --> 27:19.110
you would just leave them after
all that we've been through?

27:19.144 --> 27:21.345
Chasing Rittenhouse,

27:21.380 --> 27:23.876
I've done horrible things...

27:25.157 --> 27:27.418
become something else.

27:27.452 --> 27:30.132
How can I bring that into my home?

27:32.090 --> 27:34.191
What kind of husband or...

27:34.226 --> 27:37.421
or a father can I be
after what I've done?

27:39.473 --> 27:41.728
We should keep moving.

27:43.468 --> 27:46.437
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:46.471 --> 27:49.471
<i>♪</i>

28:02.821 --> 28:04.789
Where'd you get a spyglass like that?

28:04.823 --> 28:07.063
I told you. The future.

28:12.380 --> 28:13.781
Those men know you?

28:13.806 --> 28:15.442
I'll introduce you as volunteers,

28:15.467 --> 28:16.968
tell Rittenhouse you're patriots

28:17.002 --> 28:19.874
who've lost faith in the cause like me.

28:21.506 --> 28:24.631
But I suggest we don't
bring everyone to the party.

28:25.777 --> 28:29.076
These are idiotic, unenlightened times,

28:29.572 --> 28:31.474
but I understand.

28:32.265 --> 28:34.343
We'll leave Rufus behind.

28:34.534 --> 28:37.502
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

28:37.527 --> 28:40.527
<i>♪</i>

28:55.812 --> 28:57.412
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

28:57.437 --> 29:00.437
<i>♪</i>

29:09.891 --> 29:12.167
[clocks ticking]

29:13.328 --> 29:16.148
[clocks chiming]

29:17.742 --> 29:19.679
[doors creaking]

29:20.779 --> 29:23.180
- General Arnold.
- John.

29:23.215 --> 29:26.031
- Is Father expecting you?
- Is he home?

29:26.056 --> 29:28.179
I'd like him to meet my
friends. They want to join.

29:28.204 --> 29:30.336
- Lot of clocks.
- Father made them.

29:30.361 --> 29:32.262
He's teaching me to make them too.

29:32.390 --> 29:34.725
- He's fascinated with time.
- Hmm.

29:34.759 --> 29:37.467
- Is your father here, John?
- Do you want to help us?

29:37.492 --> 29:39.396
Is that why you're here?

29:39.431 --> 29:41.265
This is a conversation
for your father, John.

29:41.299 --> 29:44.435
[clocks ticking]

29:55.413 --> 29:57.381
Is that your clock?

29:57.415 --> 30:01.008
Yes, but I can't seem to get
the ratchet wheel to work.

30:01.033 --> 30:03.942
Father says I'm not
paying enough attention.

30:10.362 --> 30:12.459
Looks like you're doing a fine job.

30:12.484 --> 30:13.964
It's a beautiful clock.

30:13.999 --> 30:17.452
My father says that peasants
are like the hands of a clock.

30:17.477 --> 30:19.788
Around and around they go.

30:21.609 --> 30:22.740
What does that mean?

30:22.774 --> 30:25.409
Because a peasant is no more
capable of choosing his own path

30:25.443 --> 30:27.155
than the hands of a clock.

30:28.812 --> 30:30.046
Well...

30:30.454 --> 30:32.537
who chooses the path for them?

30:32.562 --> 30:34.632
The clockmaker, of course.

30:36.155 --> 30:41.046
And are the members of
Rittenhouse the clockmakers?

30:42.131 --> 30:43.699
No one else can do it.

30:43.921 --> 30:45.763
Father says monarchies are too selfish

30:45.797 --> 30:48.599
and democracies are too chaotic.

30:48.633 --> 30:51.302
So the members of
Rittenhouse are not part of,

30:51.336 --> 30:53.370
you know, any government?

30:53.405 --> 30:56.807
Not necessarily. Control
is all that matters.

30:56.841 --> 30:59.710
Usually it's best
exercised from the shadows.

30:59.744 --> 31:03.847
[clocks ticking]

31:03.882 --> 31:05.716
What about the people that want a voice

31:05.750 --> 31:07.117
in how they're controlled?

31:07.152 --> 31:08.719
Peasants can't govern themselves

31:08.753 --> 31:10.654
any more than ants can rule the jungle.

31:10.689 --> 31:13.974
Most peasants want nothing more
than the illusion of a voice.

31:13.999 --> 31:16.671
Father says that's what democracy's for.

31:16.718 --> 31:18.138
Oh.

31:18.163 --> 31:22.333
<i>[tense music]</i>

31:22.367 --> 31:26.637
What you're describing sounds like
tyranny disguised as democracy.

31:26.671 --> 31:29.373
Father believes there's no other choice.

31:29.407 --> 31:32.076
<i>♪</i>

31:32.110 --> 31:34.011
What do you believe, John?

31:34.045 --> 31:37.045
<i>♪</i>

31:38.283 --> 31:40.985
No one's ever asked me that before.

31:41.019 --> 31:43.220
[clocks ticking]

31:43.254 --> 31:45.089
[door clicking and creaking open]

31:45.123 --> 31:47.257
Benedict Arnold.

31:47.292 --> 31:50.173
You honor us with your presence.

31:51.908 --> 31:53.767
Father.

31:54.415 --> 31:56.040
That's him.

31:57.439 --> 31:59.236
David, you look well.

31:59.270 --> 32:01.005
John was just telling
my friends about you.

32:01.039 --> 32:03.205
Yes, Father. They want to join.

32:03.942 --> 32:05.736
They do?

32:06.431 --> 32:09.305
You've never brought me
recruits before, Benedict.

32:09.330 --> 32:11.782
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

32:11.816 --> 32:14.385
May I get a better look at you?

32:14.419 --> 32:17.228
My eyes aren't what they used to be.

32:19.189 --> 32:22.189
Go on. Father wants to examine you.

32:22.627 --> 32:25.627
<i>♪</i>

32:32.103 --> 32:34.747
You have good, strong teeth.

32:35.507 --> 32:38.142
- Good skull proportion.
- Stop.

32:38.176 --> 32:41.245
Your hips are a bit narrow,
but nobody's perfect.

32:41.279 --> 32:44.214
Have you reproduced yet?

32:46.221 --> 32:48.643
- No.
- Good.

32:49.854 --> 32:51.347
[gasps]

32:51.372 --> 32:52.589
Wyatt.

32:52.614 --> 32:53.659
What are you doing?

32:53.684 --> 32:55.402
No sudden movements, if you please.

32:55.427 --> 32:57.345
David, what is this?

32:57.370 --> 32:58.896
These men are here to kill me.

32:58.930 --> 33:02.018
- You got this all wrong.
- Really?

33:02.600 --> 33:04.968
The sweat on her brow.

33:05.065 --> 33:08.790
The hand near your pocket,
where I assume you have a pistol.

33:08.815 --> 33:12.876
This isn't the first time I've seen
that look on a man's face, believe me.

33:12.901 --> 33:14.940
You mean me harm.

33:15.947 --> 33:17.981
But don't worry, my dear.

33:18.016 --> 33:21.143
We'll still find a good use for you.

33:21.186 --> 33:23.287
<i>[ominous music]</i>

33:23.321 --> 33:26.323
[indistinct chatter]

33:32.697 --> 33:35.666
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:35.700 --> 33:39.837
<i>♪</i>

33:39.871 --> 33:43.114
[coughing]

33:43.418 --> 33:47.654
<i>♪</i>

33:47.679 --> 33:49.278
Get up.

33:50.014 --> 33:52.015
Boy, get up.

33:54.052 --> 33:56.019
- I said get up.
- [grunting]

33:56.054 --> 33:58.122
[all gasp]

33:58.156 --> 34:01.164
<i>♪</i>

34:04.620 --> 34:07.622
[clocks ticking]

34:11.353 --> 34:13.746
What an ingenious pistol.

34:14.693 --> 34:16.806
I've never seen its equal.

34:16.841 --> 34:18.742
You have to believe me, David.

34:18.777 --> 34:21.145
How could I have known
they were lying to me?

34:21.179 --> 34:23.426
You know all I ever want
is to be of service to you,

34:23.451 --> 34:25.549
to serve the cause.

34:25.583 --> 34:28.404
- I'm so grateful for the opp...
- Shut up, Benedict.

34:29.353 --> 34:30.989
I'm sorry, sir.

34:32.422 --> 34:35.982
Did he tell you how I
admire his military genius?

34:36.561 --> 34:39.329
How when the war is over, I
will give him a place near me

34:39.364 --> 34:40.664
at the table of elders?

34:40.697 --> 34:42.599
I'm honored, sir.

34:42.634 --> 34:46.266
But did he also tell you
about his alcoholic father?

34:47.641 --> 34:49.940
His poor education?

34:49.974 --> 34:52.176
His vanity?

34:52.210 --> 34:54.777
- His bad temper? His...
- David, please.

34:54.813 --> 34:57.212
After everything I've done for you?

34:58.550 --> 35:01.451
You're an idiot, Benedict.

35:01.486 --> 35:05.236
So blinded by your wounded pride...

35:06.751 --> 35:11.228
that you brought these people
into my house to kill me.

35:11.485 --> 35:14.965
It was just a mistake, sir.
Please. You can trust me.

35:14.999 --> 35:17.434
You betrayed your best
friend in the whole world,

35:17.468 --> 35:19.836
so why would I ever trust you?

35:20.500 --> 35:21.956
[gunshot]

35:23.073 --> 35:26.713
[gunshots]

35:30.534 --> 35:33.468
<i>[ominous music]</i>

35:33.503 --> 35:36.503
<i>♪</i>

35:38.784 --> 35:40.948
Where did you get this?

35:42.488 --> 35:44.182
No, no.

35:44.523 --> 35:46.424
Don't worry.

35:46.459 --> 35:48.416
I'm a clockmaker.

35:48.441 --> 35:50.510
I'll figure it out.

35:53.366 --> 35:55.967
- Son?
- Yes, Father?

35:56.002 --> 35:59.170
Watch. It's important that you see this.

36:03.774 --> 36:05.009
No!

36:09.385 --> 36:10.949
Please don't hurt them in front of me.

36:10.983 --> 36:14.486
Now, John, what have I
said about seeing the world

36:14.520 --> 36:16.526
as it really is?

36:17.554 --> 36:19.143
Yes, Father.

36:21.327 --> 36:23.752
You two are sentenced to death.

36:24.196 --> 36:26.031
But you...

36:26.065 --> 36:28.838
are to be brought to my bedchamber

36:28.863 --> 36:31.863
<i>♪</i>

36:40.238 --> 36:41.239
Hey!

36:41.272 --> 36:42.528
[gunshot]

36:43.079 --> 36:45.630
[all grunting]

36:45.655 --> 36:48.624
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:48.649 --> 36:50.419
<i>♪</i>

36:50.443 --> 36:51.443
Flynn!

36:51.457 --> 36:52.528
[gunshot]

36:53.859 --> 36:56.859
<i>♪</i>

37:05.738 --> 37:08.073
[both panting]

37:08.107 --> 37:11.843
[clocks ticking]

37:11.877 --> 37:14.212
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:14.246 --> 37:16.181
[gunshot]

37:16.215 --> 37:20.352
<i>♪</i>

37:20.551 --> 37:23.121
Killing me won't change anything.

37:23.155 --> 37:24.786
There are others.

37:25.157 --> 37:27.262
This will outlive me...

37:27.287 --> 37:29.137
you...

37:29.591 --> 37:31.520
all of us.

37:32.747 --> 37:34.272
Rittenhouse will become...

37:34.297 --> 37:35.697
[gunshot]

37:40.573 --> 37:42.206
You did it.

37:43.509 --> 37:45.410
You actually did it.

37:45.444 --> 37:48.446
[clocks ticking]

37:52.197 --> 37:53.965
[sighs]

37:53.990 --> 37:56.025
Where's the boy?

37:58.157 --> 38:00.624
What... the... the boy?
What do you mean the boy?

38:00.649 --> 38:02.413
The boy's gone.

38:02.898 --> 38:05.163
His son, he escaped.

38:05.197 --> 38:06.731
Are you saying that you
want to kill his son?

38:06.766 --> 38:08.800
I don't want to, but we need to.

38:08.834 --> 38:10.757
You heard; he believes the
same things as his father.

38:10.782 --> 38:13.584
You already killed Rittenhouse.
There's no need to kill the boy.

38:13.773 --> 38:16.265
<i>[tense music]</i>

38:16.290 --> 38:17.976
<i>♪</i>

38:18.010 --> 38:19.677
Flynn.

38:19.712 --> 38:21.813
<i>♪</i>

38:21.847 --> 38:23.448
Flynn.

38:23.482 --> 38:25.101
Flynn!

38:25.126 --> 38:26.702
Guys, help me out!

38:26.727 --> 38:29.696
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:29.721 --> 38:32.423
<i>♪</i>

38:32.691 --> 38:36.494
You guys find Flynn,
I'll go find the boy.

38:36.529 --> 38:39.529
<i>♪</i>

38:50.800 --> 38:52.119
No, no.

38:52.144 --> 38:54.612
[sobbing] No, please don't kill me.

38:54.647 --> 38:58.716
Please. Please. Please don't kill me.

38:58.751 --> 39:01.019
No. No, no, no. Don't kill me.

39:01.053 --> 39:03.596
Please! Please don't!

39:03.989 --> 39:05.659
Please!

39:06.618 --> 39:08.260
Please.

39:10.952 --> 39:12.880
[whispers] Don't do it.

39:13.532 --> 39:16.201
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

39:16.235 --> 39:18.336
[groans]

39:18.370 --> 39:20.171
<i>♪</i>

39:20.206 --> 39:23.174
[breathing sharply]

39:23.209 --> 39:26.209
<i>♪</i>

39:33.119 --> 39:35.520
[sighs]

39:35.554 --> 39:38.790
- Move.
- No.

39:39.152 --> 39:41.257
- Move!
- No!

39:42.638 --> 39:44.205
I'm not letting you kill a child.

39:44.230 --> 39:47.566
He's all that's left of Rittenhouse.

39:47.591 --> 39:49.375
You don't know that.

39:49.709 --> 39:51.443
He said that there were others.

39:51.468 --> 39:53.981
You don't know that killing
his son will change anything.

39:54.006 --> 39:56.375
He wants everything his father wants.

39:56.400 --> 39:59.117
When you were 12, you
wanted to be a cowboy.

40:00.146 --> 40:02.881
- People change.
- He's gonna do terrible things!

40:02.907 --> 40:04.574
Why?

40:04.617 --> 40:07.078
Because his father wants him to?

40:07.653 --> 40:09.481
You don't know that!

40:09.630 --> 40:12.265
You have a choice right now!

40:12.872 --> 40:16.161
We all have choices! We can decide...

40:16.795 --> 40:19.230
we can decide to be something different.

40:19.265 --> 40:22.233
<i>[pensive music]</i>

40:22.268 --> 40:25.937
<i>♪</i>

40:25.971 --> 40:28.242
Please, no, please.

40:28.484 --> 40:30.775
Please don't do this, please.

40:30.809 --> 40:32.810
Please.

40:32.845 --> 40:35.747
You... you said... you said
that you couldn't be a father

40:35.781 --> 40:37.815
after what you've done.

40:37.850 --> 40:40.518
But you can, okay? You can.

40:40.553 --> 40:42.487
You can go back, but not if you do this.

40:42.521 --> 40:44.122
- Please, please!
- Get out of my way.

40:44.179 --> 40:47.179
<i>♪</i>

40:50.329 --> 40:52.297
[sobbing]

40:52.331 --> 40:53.635
John?

40:54.733 --> 40:56.601
John!

40:56.635 --> 41:00.505
<i>♪</i>

41:00.539 --> 41:02.540
He's gone.

41:04.710 --> 41:06.177
- Come here!
- What?

41:06.212 --> 41:07.979
No. Where are you taking me?

41:08.013 --> 41:10.783
I thought you understood
what was at stake.

41:10.808 --> 41:12.375
Come here!

41:12.400 --> 41:13.713
<i>[ominous music]</i>

41:13.738 --> 41:15.229
- Anything?
- No, you?

41:15.254 --> 41:17.377
- Nothing.
- Wyatt!

41:17.723 --> 41:19.619
- Wyatt!
- Come on.

41:20.088 --> 41:22.024
- Lucy!
- Wyatt!

41:22.049 --> 41:24.549
- Flynn!
- Rufus!

41:25.664 --> 41:28.566
No. No!

41:28.601 --> 41:30.735
- Let go of me!
- Lucy!

41:30.769 --> 41:32.510
Wyatt!

41:33.939 --> 41:35.729
Lucy!

41:35.754 --> 41:38.223
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:38.377 --> 41:40.345
Lucy!

41:40.379 --> 41:43.781
<i>♪</i>

41:54.645 --> 41:57.645
<i>♪</i>

